Lab Name: File Path Traversal, Traversal Sequences Stripped Non-Recursively

Category: Path Traversal

Difficulty: Practitioner

Objective: Retrieve the contents of the /etc/passwd file by bypassing non-recursive traversal sequence stripping.

Vulnerability Description

The application attempts to sanitize user input by removing traversal sequences (../). However, this filtering is performed only once (non-recursively). By supplying overlapping traversal sequences, the remaining characters form valid traversal sequences after the initial stripping, allowing directory traversal.

Exploitation Steps

1. Open a product page and intercept the image request using Burp Suite.


2. Send the request to Repeater.


3. Locate the filename parameter.


4. Replace its value with the following payload:



....//....//....//etc/passwd

5. Send the request.


6. The application strips the first occurrence of traversal patterns, leaving valid ../ sequences that resolve to /etc/passwd, returning the file contents and completing the lab.

Payload

GET /image?filename=....//....//....//etc/passwd HTTP/1.1

Why the Attack Works

The application removes traversal sequences only once. The payload ....// is crafted so that after the first filtering pass, it becomes ../. Because no further sanitization occurs, the remaining traversal sequences are processed by the operating system, allowing access to directories outside the intended location.

Mitigation

Normalize the requested path before validation.

Perform canonical path validation rather than string replacement.

Restrict file access to an allowlisted directory.

Reject any input containing traversal attempts after normalization.

Avoid relying on simple string replacement as a security control.